1. Scope (Where variable is accessible)

function testScope() {
  if (true) {
    var a = 10; // function-scoped
    let b = 20; // block-scoped
    const c = 30; // block-scoped
  }

  console.log(a); // âœ… 10
  console.log(b); // âŒ ReferenceError
  console.log(c); // âŒ ReferenceError
}

testScope();


Keyword	          Scope Type
var	              Function scope
let	              Block scope {}
const	            Block scope {}


2.Re-declaration

var x = 1;
var x = 2; // âœ… Allowed

let y = 1;
// let y = 2; // âŒ SyntaxError

const z = 1;
// const z = 2; // âŒ SyntaxError

Keyword	Can Redeclare in Same Scope?
var	          âœ… Yes
let	          âŒ No
const	        âŒ No



3. Hoisting (Declared before use)

console.log(a); // âœ… undefined (hoisted)
var a = 10;

console.log(b); // âŒ ReferenceError
let b = 20;

console.log(c); // âŒ ReferenceError
const c = 30;




4. Mutability (Can change value?)

let a = 10;
a = 20; // âœ… Works

const b = 30;
// b = 40; // âŒ TypeError (cannot reassign const)

const obj = { name: "A" };
obj.name = "B"; // âœ… Allowed: object contents can be changed


5. Use Cases

Use var when... (rarely used now)
You need function-level scoping
For old code or compatibility

Use let when...
The value will change
You need block-level scope

Use const when...
The value should not change
Youâ€™re declaring constants or config

